---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Baby Weight: lbs to kg Conversion for New Parents" description="Quick baby weight conversion chart from pounds to kilograms. Understand your newborn's weight in both units with our simple reference guide for parents." keywords="baby weight conversion, lbs to kg baby, newborn weight chart, infant weight, baby weight kg to lbs, pediatric weight, baby growth chart">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Weight</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Baby Weight: lbs to kg Conversion for New Parents</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 8, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>When your baby is born, one of the first things you will hear is their weight. Depending on where you live, it might be announced in pounds and ounces or in kilograms. Here is a clear guide to help new parents understand baby weights in both systems.</p>

      <h2>The Conversion Formula</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 lb = 0.4536 kg | 1 kg = 2.2046 lbs</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Remember: 1 oz = 28.35 g (there are 16 oz in 1 lb)</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Newborn Weight Reference Chart</h2>
      <p>Here are common newborn weights converted between systems:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>5 lbs 8 oz = 2.49 kg</li>
        <li>6 lbs 0 oz = 2.72 kg</li>
        <li>6 lbs 8 oz = 2.95 kg</li>
        <li>7 lbs 0 oz = 3.18 kg</li>
        <li>7 lbs 8 oz = 3.40 kg</li>
        <li>8 lbs 0 oz = 3.63 kg</li>
        <li>8 lbs 8 oz = 3.86 kg</li>
        <li>9 lbs 0 oz = 4.08 kg</li>
        <li>9 lbs 8 oz = 4.31 kg</li>
        <li>10 lbs 0 oz = 4.54 kg</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Average Newborn Weights</h2>
      <p>According to the World Health Organisation, the average full-term newborn weighs:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Girls:</strong> 3.2 kg (7 lbs 1 oz)</li>
        <li><strong>Boys:</strong> 3.3 kg (7 lbs 4 oz)</li>
        <li><strong>Normal range:</strong> 2.5 to 4.5 kg (5 lbs 8 oz to 9 lbs 15 oz)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Converting Pounds and Ounces to Kilograms</h2>
      <p>Baby weights in the US are expressed in pounds and ounces (e.g., "7 lbs 6 oz"). To convert this to kilograms:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Convert everything to ounces: (7 × 16) + 6 = 118 oz</li>
        <li>Multiply by 28.35 to get grams: 118 × 28.35 = 3,345 g</li>
        <li>Divide by 1000 to get kilograms: 3.35 kg</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Medical records</strong> — paediatricians track growth in the metric system for WHO growth charts</li>
        <li><strong>Medicine dosing</strong> — infant medications are dosed per kilogram of body weight</li>
        <li><strong>International families</strong> — grandparents abroad may only understand one system</li>
        <li><strong>Growth percentiles</strong> — growth charts use kilograms, so you need accurate conversions</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Tracking your baby's weight gain is one of the best indicators of healthy development in the first year. Whether your doctor uses kg or lbs, now you can understand both.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/weight" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Weight Converter →</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
